%%TITLE
Cost-effectiveness of introducing the 10-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine into the universal immunisation of infants in Brazil.
%%ABSTRACT
Cost-effectiveness studies have been increasingly part of decision processes for incorporating new vaccines into the Brazilian National Immunisation Program. This study aimed to evaluate the cost-effectiveness of 10-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV10) in the universal childhood immunisation programme in Brazil.A decision-tree analytical model based on the ProVac Initiative pneumococcus model was used, following 25 successive cohorts from birth until 5 years of age. Two strategies were compared: (1) status quo and (2) universal childhood immunisation programme with PCV10. Epidemiological and cost estimates for pneumococcal disease were based on National Health Information Systems and literature. A 'top-down' costing approach was employed. Costs are reported in 2004 Brazilian reals. Costs and benefits were discounted at 3%.25 years after implementing the PCV10 immunisation programme, 10â€ˆ226 deaths, 360â€ˆ657 disability-adjusted life years (DALYs), 433â€ˆ808 hospitalisations and 5â€ˆ117â€ˆ109 outpatient visits would be avoided. The cost of the immunisation programme would be R$10â€ˆ674â€ˆ478â€ˆ765, and the expected savings on direct medical costs and family costs would be R$1â€ˆ036â€ˆ958â€ˆ639 and R$209â€ˆ919â€ˆ404, respectively. This resulted in an incremental cost-effectiveness ratio of R$778â€ˆ145/death avoided and R$22â€ˆ066/DALY avoided from the society perspective.The PCV10 universal infant immunisation programme is a cost-effective intervention (1-3 GDP per capita/DALY avoided). Owing to the uncertain burden of disease data, as well as unclear long-term vaccine effects, surveillance systems to monitor the long-term effects of this programme will be essential.
%%METHODS
Model
A decision- tree analytical model, developed by the ProVac Initiative of the Pan American Health Organization and its partners, was used to estimate the cost-effectiveness of a universal childhood immunisation programme with PCV10 in Brazil.6 An early version of the model was used. This model has since been superseded by an integrated three- way model (TriVac) developed by ProVac Initiative, which is similar in structure but was not available at the time of the analysis. An in-depth description of the model can be found on the Pan American Health Organization website.7
With the ProVac model, 25 successive cohorts were followed from birth until 5 years of age. The model captured the effects of vaccination on inva- sive disease (meningitis and sepsis together), pneumonia and acute otitis media (AOM). Vacci- nation’s effects were captured by the model as
210 J Epidemiol Community Health 2012;66:210e217. doi:10.1136/jech.2010.111880
health burden (cases, deaths, life years, disability-adjusted life years (DALYs)) and economic burden (health systems costs, family costs). The stream of events in the decision tree is shown in ﬁgure 1. The model assessed the cost-effectiveness of a child- hood immunisation programme by comparing two strategies:
(1) the current national strategy of vaccinating only high-risk children; and (2) introduction of a universal immunisation programme with PCV10 for children in their ﬁrst year of life.
According to ﬁgure 1, each strategy presents four possibilities: every child may have no PD or invasive pneumococcal disease (IPD), or pneumonia or AOM. Only vaccine-serotype PD may be averted by vaccination and the model estimated only the burden of disease caused by serotypes included in the PCV10. With PCV10, additional vaccination costs were incurred, and costs were averted when disease was avoided. Health beneﬁts were deaths and non- fatal disease cases averted by immunisation. Costs and health beneﬁts were summarised in incremental cost-effectiveness ratios. The model used did not capture the beneﬁts of the herd effect (ie, protection of the unvaccinated population) or on pneumo- coccal antibiotic-resistance, or the risk of serotype replacement
after implementing the universal vaccination.
The analysis was conducted from both the societal perspec- tive (including direct and indirect costs) and the healthcare system perspective. All costs were reported in Brazilian reals (2004 prices, US$1 R$2.65), and the time frame of the analysis was 25 years. In accordance with Brazilian and international recommendations, both health and monetary effects were discounted at a rate of 3% per year.8 9 Comprehensive univariate sensitivity analyses were performed to evaluate the effects of uncertainty in key parameters (disease incidence, serotype coverage by vaccine, case death rate, vaccine efﬁcacy, hospital- isation costs, discount rate, number of vaccine doses and price per vaccine dose) of the model. A multivariate sensitivity anal- ysis as best- and worst-case scenarios was performed simulta- neously varying parameters identiﬁed as important in the univariate analysis.
The study was approved by the Ethics Committee of the Hospital das Clínicas da Faculdade de Medicina da Universidade de São Paulo, Brazil.

The numbers of hospitalisations due to pneumococcal meningitis and pneumococcal sepsis at the public healthcare system (Sistema Único de Saúde, SUS) in 2004, the most recent year for which complete data were available at the time of data collection, were retrieved from the Hospitalisation Information System (Sistema de Informação Hospitalar, SIH/SUS).10 Data from a 2003 national household survey, which indicated the private healthcare system as responsible for 23% of overall
hospitalisations of children <5, were used to adjust the total number of hospitalisations.11 The total number of hospital- isations was divided by the <5 population to calculate IPD incidence rate in children <5 (13.59/100 000). IPD may lead to many types of sequelae, but analysis was restricted to deafness
and neurological sequelae after meningitis. The risk of sequelae after IPD was based on literature.12e15 It was assumed that 8.49% of the children evolved to deafness and 11.32% with neurological sequelae. Data from the SIH/SUS and from the Notiﬁable Diseases Information System (Sistema de Informação de Agravos de Notiﬁcação, SINAN) were used to calculate case death rates for IPD (25.02%).16
Pneumonia estimates were based on hospitalisations due to all-causes pneumonia identiﬁed in the SIH/SUS database, and adjusted to include hospitalisations at the private system. Since Brazilian data for the number of pneumonia cases treated in outpatient healthcare facilities were absent, estimates were
based on the number of hospitalisations due to pneumonia and the proportion of children <5 seen in emergency rooms who were hospitalised. Data from the Brazilian literature indicated that 40e44% of the infants and 18e28% of children aged 1e4 years with pneumonia diagnosed at the public emergency
rooms are hospitalised.17 18 A household survey showed a higher proportion of hospitalisation at the private healthcare system.19 The all-causes pneumonia incidence rate in under-5 children (93.4/1000) was estimated from the numbers of cases treated in hospital and ambulatory settings in both public and private systems, divided by the <5 population.
Data on radiologically conﬁrmed all-causes pneumonia were
used to estimate the proportion of pneumococcal pneumonia among all-causes pneumonia. Data from Brazilian literature showed that 96e100% of children <5 with suspected pneu- monia seen in emergency rooms have a chest x-ray, and 74e98% of them have radiologically conﬁrmed pneumonia.17 20 A study
indicated S pneumoniae to be responsible for 21% of radiologically conﬁrmed pneumonia in children <5.21 Based on these data, the proportion of all-causes pneumonia due to pneumococcus in hospital and outpatient settings was estimated. Standard methods were used for estimating DALYs, including age weighting, discounting and disability weights.26 Parameters and assumptions for DALYs estimates are presented in table 1.
Vaccine efficacy and vaccination programme
Vaccines were assumed to be administered in four doses at age 2, 4, 6 and 12e15 months, as in the PCV10 clinical trials.27 Since PCV10’s licensure was based on immunogenicity data, it was assumed that the PCV10 four-dose schedule efﬁcacy against vaccine-speciﬁc serotypes would be the same as the PCV7 four- dose schedule (table 1).28e32 It was assumed that the PCV10 would confer protection against pneumonia and AOM only for the ﬁrst 2 years of life, whereas vaccine’s protection against IPD would be kept unchanged until 5 years of age.29 31 32
The PCV10 was assumed to be coadministered with routine childhood vaccines (DTPw/Hib, hepatitis B and OPV). This approach avoids additional visits, reduces administration costs and enhances compliance and vaccination coverage. It was assumed that all children initiating vaccination would complete the four-dose schedule. The vaccination coverage rate was assumed to be 80% and 90%, in the ﬁrst and second year of the universal vaccination programme, and 95% from the third to the 25th year.
Possible adverse events associated with vaccination were not taken into account in this analysis.
With the current strategy of pneumococcal vaccination of high-risk children, 36 570 doses of PCV7 were administered to children <5 in 2004.33 This number was used to estimate the annual costs of the current vaccination strategy.
Costs estimates
Table 1 summarises the healthcare costs parameters. A ‘top- down’ costing approach was used. Costs were based on aggre- gate information, representing national average values paid by the Ministry of Health and healthcare organisations, considered appropriate for this study’s objectives. Hospitalisation costs were obtained from SIH/SUS system and the Tabela Única Nacional de Equivalência de Procedimentos, TUNEP), a list of procedures deﬁned by the National Health Agency (Agência Nacional de Saúde, ANS) that determines the value of
procedures performed in the Public Healthcare System/SUS for private-health-plan users, proxy costs for the private healthcare system.34 Direct costs of ambulatory treatments were obtained from the Ambulatory Information System (Sistema de Infor- mação Ambulatorial, SIA/SUS) and from the TUNEP.34 35 Ambulatory treatment costs included medical visits, diagnostic tests and medication (drug resource based on clinical guidelines). Direct family costs included transportation costs and medica- tion paid by the families. Transportation cost was calculated based on the unit cost of the average price of public trans- portation in Brazil (R$1.60) and the number of visits needed during treatment.
Indirect costs were estimated based on time lost by a parent of a child with PD using the human capital approach. Production losses were based on maternal absence from work to take care of a sick child. Maternal absence from work was valued based on the average daily income of economically active Brazilian women. Each day lost was valued at R$15.65. For each clinical syndrome, the productivity costs were calculated based on the average length of stay in hospital retrieved from SIH/SUS (10 days for IPD and 5 days for pneumonia), or the clinical course of disease treated in an ambulatory setting (5 days for pneumonia and 1 day for AOM). The model did not take into account future productivity losses due to child premature death. As the PCV10 price was still unavailable at the time the analysis was conducted, a price of US$15 (R$39.75) per vaccine dose was assumed in the base case. The assumed price was very close to the price (R$31.00) negotiated by the Ministry of Health in 2009. Following the methodology used in a previous study, the administration costs per dose were calculated as US$1 (R$2.65).36 Vaccine wastage rate was set at 5%, considering a single-dose package, and the total cost of each dose was
R$44.39.
